import dataset

library(readxl)
heart_attack = read_excel("Heart Attack Data Set.xlsx")

Normalization:

normalize <- function(x) {
  return((x - min(x)) / (max(x) - min(x)))
}

heart_attack$trestbps <- normalize(heart_attack$trestbps)
heart_attack$chol <- normalize(heart_attack$chol)
heart_attack$thalach <- normalize(heart_attack$thalach)
heart_attack$oldpeak <- normalize(heart_attack$oldpeak)
heart_attack$cp <- normalize(heart_attack$cp)
heart_attack$oldpeak <- normalize(heart_attack$oldpeak)
heart_attack$slope <- normalize(heart_attack$slope)
heart_attack$thal <- normalize(heart_attack$thal)
# Decide how many clusters to look at
n_clusters <- 10

# Initialize total within sum of squares error: wss
wss <- numeric(n_clusters)

# Look over 1 to n possible clusters
for (i in 1:n_clusters) {
  # Fit the model: km.out
  km.out <- kmeans(heart_attack, centers = i, nstart = 20)
  
  # Save the within cluster sum of squares
  wss[i] <- km.out$tot.withinss
}

# Produce a scree plot
library(ggplot2)
wss_df <- data.frame(clusters = 1:n_clusters, wss = wss)
scree_plot <- ggplot(wss_df, aes(x = clusters, y = wss, group = 1)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2, 4, 6, 8, 10)) +
  xlab("Number of clusters")

scree_plot

The scree plot shows the total within-cluster sum of squares (WSS) as a function of the number of clusters. The elbow method suggests choosing the value of k where the plot bends sharply, indicating a diminishing return of adding more clusters. In this example, the elbow seems to be at k = 2, but you can also try other values of k to compare the results.

##   cluster size ave.sil.width
## 1       1  120          0.55
## 2       2  183          0.55

he silhouette plot shows the silhouette coefficient for each observation as a horizontal bar. The bars are grouped by cluster and sorted by decreasing width. The dashed line shows the average silhouette width. The plot also shows the size and percentage of each cluster. The silhouette plot can help to identify outliers and poorly clustered observations.
